    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-03-22T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-03-22T14:00:00-05:00" n="20"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d20">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_MSA1">MSA</gloss> telegram files, <gloss target="#t_FRC1"
                        >FRC</gloss> Acc. No. 54 A 298, “Paris <gloss target="#t_Repto1"
                        >Repto</gloss>”: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 20<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Deputy United States Special Representative in Europe for
                        Economic Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_PORTERPR1" type="from"
                            >Porter</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Mutual Security
                            Agency</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d20fn1">Repeated to London for <persName
                            corresp="#p_HOLMESJC1">Holmes</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MOOREBT1">Moore</persName>, The Hague for <persName
                            corresp="#p_HUNTERCE1">Hunter</persName>, and Paris for <persName
                            corresp="#p_LABOUISSEHRJ1">Labouisse</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-03-22T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 22, 1952—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 1369. Personal for <persName
                        corresp="#p_HARRIMANWA1">Harriman</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DRAPERWHJ1">Draper</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KENNEYWJ1"
                        >Kenney</persName>, from <persName corresp="#p_PORTERPR1">Porter</persName>.
                    State pls pass to <persName corresp="#p_PERKINSGW1">Perkins</persName>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Before returning to Hague, <persName corresp="#p_STIKKERDU1"
                            >Stikker</persName> called on me this morning at my home (where I am
                        again confined with new attack of grippe) to discuss developments re next
                        week’s meeting <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> council of
                        ministers.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>He was discouraged by <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName>’s
                        coolness toward <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> as indicated in
                        private dinner of <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_STIKKERDU1">Stikker</persName> Thursday evening.
                        He said also <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> had made no
                        comment on speeches <persName corresp="#p_LANGEH1">Lange</persName>, and
                            <persName corresp="#p_ZEELANDPV1">Van Zeeland</persName> made in
                        ministerial comite of Council of Europe to effect that <gloss
                            target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> confronted with critical situation and
                        support of all its members urgently needed.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Appraising present situation discussing strategy for next week’s meeting,
                            <persName corresp="#p_STIKKERDU1">Stikker</persName> and I found
                        ourselves in agreement on fol: <list>
                            <label>(a)</label>
                            <item>Current crisis in <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> is not
                                simply crisis for an organization. Economic cooperation in Western
                                    <gloss target="#t_EUR1">Eur</gloss> is faltering seriously, and
                                widespread return to bilateralism in trade and payments this year a
                                real danger.</item>
                            <label>(b)</label>
                            <item>Breakdown of econ cooperation would radically affect <gloss
                                    target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> milit build-up and would also
                                have important bearing on internal polit developments in several
                                major countries, with perhaps significant effect on govts foreign
                                policy.</item>
                            <label>(c)</label>
                            <item>Solution to present crisis is to be found in bold new step
                                forward, not in temporizing or retreat. While UK and Fr import cuts
                                must be accepted as fact, council should call on both govts to put
                                forward acceptable programs for early return to liberalization. More
                                authoritative <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> trade body
                                should be established (now designated tentatively as trade managing
                                board). Council shld establish <pb facs="0091" n="43" xml:id="pg_43"
                                /> ministerial group on mutual financial stability. Good progress
                                made by minis group on coal production provides precedent for
                                similar approach to finan stability. Moreover, objectives of higher
                                production must be pressed. Finally, <gloss target="#t_OEEC1"
                                    >OEEC</gloss> must develop realistic program to provide support
                                necessary for annual <gloss target="#t_TCC1">TCC</gloss>-type
                                operation in <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>.</item>
                            <label>(d)</label>
                            <item>No significant compromises can be made with Brit on foregoing
                                insofar as they are not prepared for full-scale action by <gloss
                                    target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss>. In my view, not only will it be
                                impossible to compromise with Brit on future functions <gloss
                                    target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss>, but I believe positive
                                understanding is necessary at an early date. Such understanding also
                                necessary to permit <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> to
                                function operationally.</item>
                            <label>(e)</label>
                            <item>Every effort should be made to reach satis agreement at
                                forthcoming mtg. There will be further opportunity at later meeting
                                to be held soon after <persName corresp="#p_STIKKERDU1"
                                    >Stikker</persName>’s return from Wash, i.e., later April or
                                May, to consolidate understanding of role of <gloss
                                    target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss>.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>I propose to outline above appraisal and proposed method of approach to
                        French (probably <persName corresp="#p_SCHUMANR1">Schuman</persName>) in
                        meeting which <persName corresp="#p_LABOUISSEHRJ1">Labouisse</persName>
                        arranging early next week.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Incidentally, <persName corresp="#p_MARJOLINRE1">Marjolin</persName> told
                        me in separate visit this morning he plans to resign unless <gloss
                            target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> soon comes to grips with basic problems.
                        He is passing this word to heads of all delegations.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BUTLERRA1">Butler</persName> was unable receive me
                        Friday as earlier indicated. Meeting with him now unlikely before
                        ministerial meeting.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MERCHANTLT1">Merchant</persName> concurs in above and
                        we both feel that every effort must be made before <gloss target="#t_OEEC1"
                            >OEEC</gloss> meeting to moderate present UK position but failing
                        success then our attitude must be such as to temporize or otherwise avoid
                        situation in which Brit–US rift revealed to all. Situation he believes
                        underlines importance direct approach Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_ACHESOND1">Acheson</persName> to <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> in this matter.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PORTERPR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Porter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
